context: <a0_0><a7_0>Between 1836 and 1842<a7_0/><a0_0/> Victorian Aboriginal groups were largely dispossessed[by whom?] of their land. By January 1844, there were said to be <a1_0><a4_0>675<a4_0/><a1_0/> Aborigines resident in squalid camps in Melbourne. <a2_0>The British Colonial Office<a2_0/> appointed <a5_0>five<a5_0/> Aboriginal Protectors for the Aborigines of Victoria, in 1839, however their work was nullified by a land policy that favoured squatters to take possession of Aboriginal lands. By <a6_0>1845<a6_0/>, fewer than <a3_0>240 wealthy Europeans<a3_0/> held all the pastoral licences then issued in Victoria and became a powerful political and economic force in Victoria for generations to come.
